Step 1: Calculate the Debt to Equity Ratio  
• From the balance sheet, Total Liabilities (only current liabilities are provided) = 3,389,719.66  
• Total Owner’s Equity = 16,111,731.83  
• Debt to Equity Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Owner’s Equity  
  = 3,389,719.66 / 16,111,731.83 ≈ 0.21  

Step 2: Calculate the Net Profit Margin  
• From the income statement, Net Profit = 111,731.83 and Total Revenue = 791,992.51  
• Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) * 100  
  = (111,731.83 / 791,992.51) * 100 ≈ 14.11%  

Step 3: Calculate the Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio  
• From the cash flow statement, Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –4,504,752.68  
• Current Liabilities = 3,389,719.66  
• Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio = Operating Cash Flow / Current Liabilities  
  = –4,504,752.68 / 3,389,719.66 ≈ –1.33  

Thus, the result is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.21",
    "Net Profit Margin": "14.11%",
    "operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio": "-1.33"
  }
}
